label: Drinking water score
definition: Whether the household drinking water source was categorized as improved or unimproved, based on WHO definitions. Drinking water sources categorized as 'Improved' include water that is 'Piped into dwelling' or 'Piped into yard or plot,' or from a 'Public tap or stand pipe;' a 'Tube well or borehole;' or a 'Protected well.' Drinking water sources categorized as 'Unimproved' include water that is from an 'Unprotected well' or 'Surface water.' Other sources of drinking water were considered 'Improved,' except for Peru where it was considered 'Unimproved' due to site-specific circumstances. Socioeconomic status was assessed every 6 months from 6-24 months and again at 60 months of age, with optional assessments from 30-60 months.
codebookDescription: Score of drinking water source; 0  for unimproved categories, 4 for improved categories. Source=FSE(derived). if fsewdrink = ''01'',''02'',''03'',''04'',''05'',''08'' then newdrink=4, ''improved'' except for pel where fsewdrink=''08'' is also considered unimproved due to site-specific circumstances; if fsewdrink = ''06'',''07'' then newdrink=0 ''unimproved'', except for pel where values of ''08'' for fsewdrink are considered unimproved

definition: Household wealth index from | Sum of 8 variables: (i) 'Bank account,' (ii) 'Bed,' (iii) 'Chair,' (iv) 'Table,' (v) 'Television,' (vi) 'Refrigerator,' (vii) 'Separate kitchen,' (vii) 'Fewer than 2 people per room.' Positive responses for each of these variables got a score of 1 while negative responses got a score of 0. Used as a component in calculating the WAMI index and ranged from 0 (low) to 8 (high). Socioeconomic status was assessed every 6 months from 6-24 months and again at 60 months of age, with optional assessments from 30-60 months. | The Household Wealth Index (HWI) is a cumulative living standard, calculated using easy-to-collect data on ownership of selected assets, such as televisions and bicycles, materials used for housing construction, types of water access, and sanitation facilities (continuous variable).
codebookDescription: Household wealth index, numerical | Wealth index from PCA | asset index | sum of 8 assets scores. Has?: mattress,chair,table,tv,refrigertaor,bank account,kitchen, < 2 people per room. Positive reponses for each of these get a score of 1 while negative responses get 0. . Source=FSE(derived). range 0-8

label: Income score
definition: Average monthly income for the entire household, converted to US Dollars, categorized into all-site noniles. Used as a component in calculating the WAMI index. Values ranged from 0 (low) to 8 (high). Socioeconomic status was assessed every 6 months from 6-24 months and again at 60 months of age, with optional assessments from 30-60 months.
codebookDescription: Reported income in US Dollars, catgeorized in all-site noniles. Source=FSE(derived). income category cutoffs, noniles of ''newincome'' (created using income data up to 36 months):0: <=36.6; 1: >=36.62 & <=65.7; 2: >=65.8 & <=90.9; 3: >=90.972 & <=111.84; 4: >=111.93 & <=140.72; 5: >=140.76 & <=180.65; 6: >=180.8 & <=250; 7: >=250.05 & <=353.2; 8: >=353.338

label: Maternal education score
definition: Years of schooling that the participant's mother had completed, divided by 2. Used as a component in calculating the WAMI index. Values ranged from 0 (low) to 8 (high). Socioeconomic status was assessed every 6 months from 6-24 months and again at 60 months of age, with optional assessments from 30-60 months.
codebookDescription: How many years of schooling have you completed?. Source=FSE. 00-20

label: Overall socioeconomic score
definition: Sum of all 4 components used to calculate the WAMI index: (i) 'Sanitation and drinking water score,' (ii) 'Assets score,' (iii) 'Income score,' and (iv) 'Maternal education score.' Values ranged from 0 (low) to 32 (high). Socioeconomic status was assessed every 6 months from 6-24 months and again at 60 months of age, with optional assessments from 30-60 months.
codebookDescription: sum of all WAMI component scores. Source=FSE(derived). 0-32

label: Sanitation and drinking water score
definition: Sum of sanitation and drinking water scores. Used as a component in calculating the WAMI index. Households with 'Drinking water categorization' and 'Sanitation categorization' variables classified as 'improved' got a score of 4 for each; 'unimproved' responses got a score of 0 for each. Values ranged from 0 (low) to 8 (high). Socioeconomic status was assessed every 6 months from 6-24 months and again at 60 months of age, with optional assessments from 30-60 months.
codebookDescription: Sum of saniation and drinking scores. . Source=FSE(derived). range 0-8

label: WAMI index
definition: An index of socio-economic status that includes access to improved water and sanitation, eight selected assets, maternal education, and household income. The WAMI index was calculated by dividing the 'Overall socioeconomic score' by 32. Values ranged from 0 (low) to 1 (high). Socioeconomic status was assessed every 6 months from 6-24 months and again at 60 months of age, with optional assessments from 30-60 months.
codebookDescription: The wami is calculated by summing values of the following variables: sanitation, asset, incat, newfseschool and dividing the total by 32. Source=FSE(derived). range 0-1

label: 1st day of ALRI episode
definition: Whether this was the first day of an acute lower respiratory Infection (ALRI) episode. ALRI episodes were separated by 14 ALRI-free days. Days when data are missing were classified as ALRI-free (if there were 14 missing days before a day with ALRI, the episode started on day with ALRI). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: 1 if first day of episode, 0 if not. calculated, ALRI

label: ALRI episode #
definition: All days of observation that fall within an acute lower respiratory Infection (ALRI) episode are coded with the ALRI episode count. ALRI episodes were separated by 14 ALRI-free days. Days when data are missing were classified as ALRI-free (if there were 14 missing days before a day with ALRI, the episode started on day with ALRI). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: All days in episode coded with number of episode. calculated, ALRI

label: ALRI episode status
definition: Whether this day of observation marked the beginning of a acute lower respiratory infection (ALRI) episode or was within an ALRI episode. ALRI episodes were separated by 14 ALRI-free days. Days when data are missing were classified as ALRI-free (if there were 14 missing days before a day with ALRI, the episode started on day with ALRI). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: 2 at beginning of episode, 1 within episode. ALRI episodes are separated by 14 ALRI-free days. In this dataset, days when data are missing are thought to be ALRI-free (so if there are 14 missing days before a day with ALRI, the episode starts on the ALRI

label: ALRI, fieldworker assessment
definition: Whether the field worker determined that the participant had an acute lower respiratory Infection (ALRI) during the surveillance visit. Participants who had a cough or shortness of breath PLUS rapid respiratory rate (defined as: >60 breaths/min in participants aged 0 to <2 months, >50 breaths/min in participants aged 2 to <12 months and >40 breaths/min in participants aged 12 months to three years) were determined to have ALRI and were referred to the nearest health center for assessment and treatment. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Fieldworker assessment of ALRI, 1=yes, 0=no, original SAF data

label: Cumulative ALRI episode count
definition: Cumulative count of acute lower respiratory Infection (ALRI) episodes since beginning of follow-up. ALRI episodes were separated by 14 ALRI-free days. Days when data are missing were classified as ALRI-free (if there were 14 missing days before a day with ALRI, the episode started on day with ALRI). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Cumulative number of ALRI episodes. calculated, ALRI

label: Cumulative days in this ALRI episode
definition: Cumulative count of days that fall within the current acute lower respiratory Infection (ALRI) episode. ALRI episodes were separated by 14 ALRI-free days. Days when data are missing were classified as ALRI-free (if there were 14 missing days before a day with ALRI, the episode started on day with ALRI). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Day of ALRI episode. calculated, ALRI

label: Cumulative days with ALRI
definition: Cumulative count of days where an acute lower respiratory Infection (ALRI) was identified since beginning of follow-up. Days when data are missing were classified as ALRI-free. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Cumulative number of days when ALRI was identified. calculated, ALRI

label: Cumulative days within ALRI episodes
definition: Cumulative count of days that fall within any acute lower respiratory Infection (ALRI) episode since beginning of follow-up. ALRI episodes were separated by 14 ALRI-free days. Days when data are missing were classified as ALRI-free (if there were two missing days before a day with ALRI, the episode started on day with ALRI). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Cumulative number of days in ALRI episode (episodes separated by 14 ALRI-'free' days). calculated, ALRI

label: Day in ALRI episode
definition: Whether this day of observation falls within an acute lower respiratory Infection (ALRI) episode. ALRI episodes were separated by 14 ALRI-free days. Days when data are missing were classified as ALRI-free (if there were 14 missing days before a day with ALRI, the episode started on day with ALRI). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: 1 for all days in episode (all days with 'ALRI'). calculated, ALRI

label: Study-defined ALRI
definition: Whether the participant had an acute lower respiratory Infection (ALRI). Participants who had a cough or shortness of breath (today or yesterday) PLUS a rapid respiratory rate (defined as: >60 breaths/min in participants aged 0 to <2 months, >50 breaths/min in participants aged 2 to <12 months and >40 breaths/min in participants aged 12 months to three years) were determined to have ALRI. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: 1 if ALRI, 0 if no ALRI. ALRI definition met when 1) Child had cough or shortness of breath (today or yesterday) & 2) Rapid respiration rate today (average of two measurements) as defined by a) >60 when child is <60 days old, b) >50 when child is >60-<365

label: Baby food type
definition: Assessed for each day.
codebookDescription: Baby Feeding (BF) History *

label: Breastfeeding data present today
definition: Whether breastfeeding data was present today or not. Data were generally collected for yesterday's diet (ie, the day prior to the day the field worker is in the home). Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: Whether the data was present today (1) or not (0). For bf, data were generally collected for yesterday's diet, ie, the day prior to the day the field worker is in the home.. Source=calculated. 1=yes, 0=no.

label: Breastfeeding status
definition: Breastfeeding status was changed starting with the first occasion clear liquid, animal milk, formula, or solid food were given, and did not allow for back and forth. Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: These calculations change feeding definitions starting with the first occasion.  They do not allow for back and forth.. Source=calculated. 0 during exclusive breastfeeding, 1 when any non-breast milk feeding starts until last breastmilk reported, 2 after last breast milk is ingested.t

label: Cumulative days exclusively breastfed
definition: Cumulative sum of days with exclusive breastfeeding (ie, number of days, from birth to date, that the participant was reported to be exclusively breastfed). Between birth and the 1st bi-weekly breastfeeding survey, participants who began breastfeeding at all were considered to be exclusively breastfed. Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age. | Assessed at each week of observation and prior to each diarrheal episode.
codebookDescription: Cumulative days of exclusive breastfeeding from birth. This is a cumulative sum of the variable ''excrun'', i.e., number of days, to date from birth, that the child was reported to be exclusively breastfed. This has been filled in between birth and minage with EBF if child began breastfeeding at all (cafbegbf~=.). Exclusive breastfeeding prevalence can be calculated by dividing cumexc / age (or days of follow up). This is a cumulative sum so that we can merge this dataset with others and determine what percent of the time a child was exclusively, predominantly, partially, and not breastfed prior to some outcome (anthro, illness, etc.).. Source=calculated. | Number of exclusive breastfeeding days prior to the episode | Number of exclusive breastfeeding days at that visit

label: Cumulative days not breastfed
definition: Cumulative sum of days with no breastfeeding (ie, number of days, from birth to date, that the participant was reported to not be breastfed). Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: Cumulative days of no breastfeeding (cumulative sum of nobfrun, ie, number of days from birth, to date, that the child was reported to not be breastfed).. This is a cumulative sum so that we can merge this dataset with others and determine what percent of the time a child was exclusively, predominantly, partially, and not breastfed prior to some outcome (anthro, illness, etc.).. Source=calculated.

label: Cumulative days partially breastfed
definition: Cumulative sum of days with partial breastfeeding (ie, number of days, from birth to date, that the participant was reported to be partially breastfed). Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: Cumulative days of partial breastfeeding (cumulative sum of partrun, ie, number of days, to date, that the child was reported to be partially breastfed).. New predominant and partial variables considering animal milk to be ingested with tea in Pakistan (even if animal milk is not indicated on the SAF). Source=calculated.

label: Cumulative days predominantly breastfed
definition: Cumulative sum of days with predominant breastfeeding (ie, number of days, from birth to date, that the participant was reported to be predominantly breastfed). Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: Cumulative days of predominant breastfeeding (cumulative sum of predrun, ie, number of days, to date, that the child was reported to be predominantly breastfed).. New predominant and partial variables considering animal milk to be ingested with tea in Pakistan (even if animal milk is not indicated on the SAF). Source=calculated.

label: Dairy reported at last visit
definition: Whether presence of dairy (milk, formula, yogurt, cheese, or other dairy products) in the diet was reported at the last breastfeeding surveillance visit. Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: Dairy intake (milk, formula, yogurt, cheese, or other dairy products, as reported on the SAF or MOA). This is a simple variable that reflects the presence of dairy in the diet at last reported diet day.. Source=calculated.

label: Exclusively breastfed at last visit
definition: Whether exclusive breastfeeding (breastfeeding present with no other liquids or solids) was reported at the last visit. Participants could switch back and forth between exclusive and different types of non-exclusive breastfeeding. Data between breastfeeding surveillance visits were filled in forward. Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: Exclusive breastfeeding (breastfeeding present, no liquid, no solids). This is a simple variable that reflects the exclusive breastfeeding status at last reported diet day. Children can switch back and forth between exclusive and different types of non-exclusive breastfeeding.. These variables provide the breastfeeding category at the last visit (since data between visits are filled in forward).. Source=calculated.

label: Not breastfed at last visit
definition: Whether no breastfeeding was reported at the last visit. Participants could switch back and forth between exclusive and different types of non-exclusive breastfeeding. Data between breastfeeding surveillance visits were filled in forward. Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: No breastfeeding reported at last reported diet day.. These variables provide the breastfeeding category at the last visit (since data between visits are filled in forward).. Source=calculated.

label: Partially breastfed at last visit
definition: Whether partial breastfeeding (breastfeeding present with solids, animal milk (considering animal milk to be ingested with tea in Pakistan), and/or formula) was reported at the last visit. Participants could switch back and forth between exclusive and different types of non-exclusive breastfeeding. Data between breastfeeding surveillance visits were filled in forward. Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: Partial breastfeeding (breastfeeding present with solids, milks, and/or formula) This is a simple variable that reflects the breastfeeding status at last reported diet day.. New predominant and partial variables considering animal milk to be ingested with tea in Pakistan (even if animal milk is not indicated on the SAF). Source=calculated.

label: Predominantly breastfed at last visit
definition: Whether predominant breastfeeding (breastfeeding and clear liquids (water, fruit juice, tea, other liquids) present, with no solids, animal milk (considering animal milk to be ingested with tea in Pakistan), or formula) was reported at the last visit. Participants could switch back and forth between exclusive and different types of non-exclusive breastfeeding. Data between breastfeeding surveillance visits were filled in forward. Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: Predominant breastfeeding (breastfeeding present, clear liquids (water, fruit juice, tea, other liquids), no solids, no milk or formula). This is a simple variable that reflects the breastfeeding status at last reported diet day.. New predominant and partial variables considering animal milk to be ingested with tea in Pakistan (even if animal milk is not indicated on the SAF). Source=calculated.

label: Acute diarrheal episode (less than 7 days)
definition: Whether the diarrhea episode was acute, defined in the MAL-ED study as lasting less than 7 days in duration. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: acute diarrhea?. Information from illness dataset:  if dur<7 then acute =1, else acute=0. Source=. 1=yes;0=no

label: Combined Vesikari and Clark severity at episode
definition: Combination of Vesikari and Clark severity scales, calculated by summing 'Diarrhea duration categorization,' 'Max loose stools per day categorization,' 'Days with vomiting at episode categorization,' 'Max dehydration categorization,' and 'Fever at episode categorization.' Possible values ranged from 1 (least severe) to 14 (most severe). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Sum of dur_sc + ls_sc + vom_sc + dehyd_sc + fev_sc (range 1-14, combination of Vesikari and Clark severity scale based on data available). Calculated. Diarrhea episode characteristics. | combination of Vesikari and Clark diarrhea severity scale based on data available from SAF. Sum of dur_sc + ls_sc + vom_sc + dehyd_sc + fev_sc (range 1-14, combination of Vesikari and Clark severity scale based on data available). From illness dataset. Source=illnessfull.csv. range 1-12

label: Days with vomiting at episode categorization
definition: Categorization of the total number of days where vomiting occurred during this diarrheal episode. Used to calculate 'Combined Vesikari and Clark severity at episode.' Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Sum of days with vomiting score (1: 1 day; 2: 2 days; 3: 3+ days with vomiting during diarrhea episode). Calculated. Diarrhea episode characteristics. | Sum of days with vomiting score. From illness dataset. Source=. 1: 1 day; 2: 2 days; 3: 3+ days with vomiting during diarrhea episode

label: Diarrhea duration categorization
definition: Categorization of the number of days this diarrheal episode lasted. Used to calculate 'Combined Vesikari and Clark severity at episode.' Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Duration of episode score (1: 2-4 days; 2: 5-7 days; 3: 8+ days). Calculated. Diarrhea episode characteristics. | Duration of episode score. From illness dataset. Source=illnessfull.csv. 1= 2-4 days; 2= 5-7 days; 3= 8+ days

label: Fever at episode categorization
definition: Categorization of fever reported during the diarrheal episode. Used to calculate 'Combined Vesikari and Clark severity at episode.' Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Fever information during a diarrhea episode. From illness dataset. Source=illnessfull.csv. 0 if no fever was reported during episode, 1 if mother reported fever, 2 if fever was confirmed by field worker (defined as >37.5 oc). | 0 if no fever was reported during episode, 1 if mother reported fever, 2 if fever was confirmed by field worker (defined as >37.5 oC).. Calculated. Diarrhea episode characteristics.

label: Max dehydration categorization
definition: Categorization of the maximum severity of dehydration that occurred during this diarrheal episode. Used to calculate 'Combined Vesikari and Clark severity at episode.' Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Maximum dehydration score. From illness dataset. Source=illnessfull.csv. 2= some dehydration; 3= severe dehydration reported during diarrhea episode | Maximum dehydration score (2: some dehydration; 3: severe dehydration reported during diarrhea episode). Calculated. Diarrhea episode characteristics.

label: Max loose stools per day categorization
definition: Categorization of the maximum number of loose stools that occurred on a single day during this diarrheal episode. Used to calculate 'Combined Vesikari and Clark severity at episode.' Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Maximum number of loose stools score. From illness dataset. Source=illnessfull.csv. 1= <5; 2= 5-7; 3= 8+ loose stools | Maximum number of loose stools score (1: <5; 2: 5-7; 3: 8+ loose stools). Calculated. Diarrhea episode characteristics.

label: Moderate-to-severe diarrhea by GEMS criteria
definition: Whether the GEMS definition of moderate-to-severe diarrhea was met during this diarrheal episode. The GEMS definition was met when the diarrheal episode was accompanied by any of the following: some or severe dehydration, dysentery (blood reported by mother in stool), hospitalization for diarrhea. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: GEMS definition of moderate/severe diarrhea episode - Episode accompanied by any of the following: Some or severe dehydration, dysentery (blood reported by mother in stool), hospitalization for diarrhea. Source=calculated. 1=yes;0=no | GEMS definition of moderate/severe diarrhea episode - Episode accompanied by any of the following: Some or severe dehydration, dysentery (blood reported by mother in stool), hospitalization for diarrhea. Calculated. Diarrhea episode characteristics.

label: Persistent diarrheal episode (more than 14 days)

codebookDescription: Is diarrhea persistent, lasting greater than 14 days?. Information from illness dataset:  If Dur>14, then persistent =1, else persistent =0. Source=PID. 1=yes;0=no | Indicator of persistent diarrhea (diarrhea lasting for at least 14 days)
codebookValues: , 0, 1 | 1 = persistent diarrhea, 0 = did no have persistent diarrhea

label: Prolonged diarrheal episode (7 to 14 days)

definition: Whether this is the first day of a diarrheal episode. Diarrhea episodes were separated by two diarrhea-free days. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: 1 if first day of episode, 0 if not, calculated. General diarrhea data (removes LM induced diarrhea).

label: Referral, fieldworker assessment
definition: Whether the field worker referred the participant for medical care during the surveillance visit. The participant was referred to the nearest health center for assessment and treatment if: (i) their temperature was above 39C; (ii) they passed 8 or more loose stools in a 24 hour period; (iii) had blood in their stool; (iv) had severe dehydration; or (v) if the field worker determined that the participant had an acute lower respiratory infection (ALRI). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Referral made by field worker, 1=yes, 0=no, original SAF data

label: Dehydration, caregiver report
definition: Participant's dehydration level, as reported by the mother. No dehydration was defined as: non-sunken eyes, no lethargy, easily consoled if irritable, drinks or breastfeeds well, normal abdominal skin pinch. Some dehydration was defined as: irritable/difficult to console, delay in skin pinch return, eyes sunken, when offered liquid drinks eagerly/demonstrates greater than normal thirst. Severe dehydration was defined as: lethargy, sunken eyes, listless, difficulty in mother/child interaction. If the mother reported severe dehydration, the participant was referred to the nearest health center for assessment and treatment. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Maternal report of dehydration (None=0, Some=1, Severe=2), original SAF data | Was children dehydrated? Maternal report of dehydration. From illness dataset. Source=illnessfull.csv. 1=yes;0=no

label: Diarrhea case during the last 2 days, caregiver report
definition: Whether the participant was classified as a diarrhea case within the last 2 days. To meet the definition for a diarrhea case, the participant must have had 3+ loose or watery stools in 24 hours OR 1+ stool with blood. Caregiver reported symptoms were assessed in target children 1 year after intervention initiation (midline, when target children were 8-15m of age) and 2 years after intervention initiation (endline, when target children were 21-27m of age). Caregiver reported symptoms were also assessed in sibling/neighbor participants at enrollment, midline, and endline.
codebookDescription: * Diarrhea case, 2d recall

label: Diarrhea case during the last 7 days, caregiver report
definition: Whether the participant was classified as a diarrhea case within the last 7 days. To meet the definition for a diarrhea case, the participant must have had 3+ loose or watery stools in 24 hours OR 1+ stool with blood. This variable, with a 7-day recall period, was used in the primary analysis to improve power as there was no evidence for differential recall by arm. Caregiver reported symptoms were assessed in target children 1 year after intervention initiation (midline, when target children were 8-15m of age) and 2 years after intervention initiation (endline, when target children were 21-27m of age). Caregiver reported symptoms were also assessed in sibling/neighbor participants at enrollment, midline, and endline.
codebookDescription: * Diarrhea case, 7d recall

2 - Uncomplicated malaria > 14 days since last episode = AL
3 - Complicated malaria > 14 days since last episode = Quinine or IV artesunate
4 - Uncomplicated Malaria < = 14 days since treatment with AL = Quinine
5 - Complicated Malaria < = 14 days since treatment with AL = Quinine or  IV artesunate
6 - Uncomplicated Malaria < = 14 days since complicated malaria = Quinine + clindamycin
7 - Complicated Malaria < = 14 days since complicated malaria = Quinine + clindamycin
8 - Uncomplicated malaria during the 1st trimester of pregnancy = Quinine
9-  uncomplicated Malaria and < 5kg = Quinine

label: Total ALRI episodes
definition: Total number of distinct acute lower respiratory infection (ALRI) episodes reported. ALRI episodes were separated by 14 ALRI-free days. Days when data were missing were classified as ALRI-free (if there were 14 missing days before a day with ALRI, the episode started on day with ALRI). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Sum of ALRI episodes. calculated, ALRI

label: Total days in all ALRI episodes
definition: Total number of days that fall within any acute lower respiratory infection (ALRI) episode since beginning of follow-up. ALRI episodes were separated by 14 ALRI-free days. Days when data were missing were classified as ALRI-free (if there were 14 missing days before a day with ALRI, the episode started on day with ALRI). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Sum of days in ALRI episode (episodes separated by 14 ALRI-'free' days). calculated, ALRI

label: Total days in all diarrheal episodes
definition: Total number of days that fall within any diarrheal episode since beginning of follow-up. Diarrhea episodes were separated by two diarrhea-free days. Days when data were missing were classified as diarrhea-free (if there were two missing days before a day with diarrhea, the episode started on day with diarrhea). Days with Lactulose:Mannitol (L:M)-induced diarrhea were classified as diarrhea-free. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Total number of days with diarrhea (sum of dprev3), calculated. General diarrhea data (removes LM induced diarrhea). | Total duration of diarrhea (sum of episode duration)

label: Total days in all diarrheal episodes, ex 1st days
definition: Total number of days that fall within any diarrheal episode during follow-up, excluding the first day of each diarrheal episode. To calculate the time at risk for a new diarrheal episode, subtract 'Total days in all diarrheal episodes' from 'Total diarrheal surveillance days.' Diarrhea episodes were separated by two diarrhea-free days. Days when data were missing were classified as diarrhea-free (if there were two missing days before a day with diarrhea, the episode started on day with diarrhea). Days with Lactulose:Mannitol (L:M)-induced diarrhea were classified as diarrhea-free. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebookDescription: Sum of days spent in diarrheal episodes, without including first day of episodes (used to subtract from sumsurv for the incidence denominator âÃÃ¶âÃâÂ¨ time at risk for a new diarrheal episode), calculated. General diarrhea data (removes LM induced diarrhea).

label: Age 1st animal milk or formula given (days)
definition: Age in days at which first animal milk (including animal milk ingested with tea in Pakistan) or formula was given. This variable changed feeding definitions for 'Breastfeeding status' and 'Age last exclusively breastfed (days)' starting with the first occasion animal milk or formula were given, and did not allow for back and forth. Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: Age at which first milk is given. New predominant and partial variables considering animal milk to be ingested with tea in Pakistan (even if animal milk is not indicated on the SAF). Source=calculated.

label: Age 1st animal milk or solids given (days)

This variable changed feeding definitions for 'Breastfeeding status' and 'Age last exclusively breastfed (days)' starting with the first occasion animal milk or solids were given, and did not allow for back and forth. Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: Age at which first milk OR solids is given. New predominant and partial variables considering animal milk to be ingested with tea in Pakistan (even if animal milk is not indicated on the SAF). Source=calculated.

Breastfeeding surveillance occurred twice per week throughout 24 or 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: Age at which first clear liquid is given. New predominant and partial variables considering animal milk to be ingested with tea in Pakistan (even if animal milk is not indicated on the SAF). Source=calculated.

label: Cumulative sum Adenovirus-pos 1st diarrheal stools
definition: Cumulative sum of first diarrheal stool samples positive for Adenovirus by ELISA to date per participant. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age).
codebookDescription: cumulative count of the number of positive adenovirus samples by PID in first diarrhea stools. . Source=Calculated. continuous numeric

label: Cumulative sum Adenovirus-pos 1st monthly stools
definition: Cumulative sum of first monthly asymptomatic stool samples positive for Adenovirus by ELISA to date per participant. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebookDescription: cumulative count of the number of positive adenovirus samples by PID in first monthly stools. . Source=Calculated. continuous numeric

label: Cumulative sum Adenovirus-pos stools
definition: Cumulative sum of stool samples positive for Adenovirus by ELISA to date per participant. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebookDescription: cumulative count of the number of positive adenovirus samples by PID. . Source=Calculated. continuous numeric

label: Cumulative sum Campylobacter-pos 1st diarrheal stools, by ELISA
definition: Cumulative sum of first diarrheal stool samples positive for Campylobacter by ELISA to date per participant. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age).
codebookDescription: cumulative count of the number of positive Campylobacter samples by PID in first diarrhea stools. . Source=Calculated. continuous numeric

label: Cumulative sum Campylobacter-pos 1st diarrheal stools, by bacteriology
definition: Cumulative sum of first diarrheal stool samples positive for Campylobacter by bacteriology culture to date per participant. Note: do not use Campylobacter culture results for analysis unless performing a specific analysis investigating Campylobacter in culture. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebookDescription: cumulative count of the number of culture-positive Campylobacter samples by PID in first diarrhea stools. . Source=Calculated. continuous numeric

label: Completely tested diarrheal stool
definition: Whether this stool sample was collected during a diarrheal episode and was completely tested. This variable was used to identify samples for diarrheal stool analyses. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age).
parentLabel: Complete testing of diarrheal stool samples

label: 1st diarrheal stool
definition: Whether this was the first diarrheal stool sample collected for a specific diarrheal episode. Note: most analyses used only the first diarrheal stool sample collected for a specific episode and not additional per-protocol diarrheal samples collected after 14 days of study-defined diarrhea. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age).

label: Analysis stool, diarrhea
definition: Whether this was the first diarrheal stool sample collected for a specific diarrheal episode and microbiology testing was completed according to the MAL-ED protocol. Use this variable to select appropriate diarrhea stools for microbiology analyses. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age).

label: Cumulative 1st diarrheal stool count
definition: Cumulative count of the number of first diarrheal stool sample collected for specific diarrheal episodes to date. Note: most analyses used only the first diarrheal stool sample collected for a specific episode and not additional per-protocol diarrheal samples collected after 14 days of study-defined diarrhea. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age).

label: Cumulative per protocol diarrheal stool count
definition: Cumulative count of the number of stool samples collected per the MAL-ED study protocol to date. Per protocol diarrheal stools included samples collected before the end of each diarrheal episode (whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day) as well as additional stool samples collected for a specific diarrhea episode after 14 study-defined diarrhea days in the same episode. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Diarrheal stool samples were collected until 36 months of age.

label: Diarrhea severity score
definition: Combination of Vesikari and Clark scales for diarrhea within -/+ 2 days of stool collection. Values can range from 1 (least severe) to 14 (most severe). Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: severity score for diarrhea days within +/2 days of stool collection. Source=illnessfull.

label: Diarrheal stool
definition: Whether this stool sample was considered a diarrheal stool by the MAL-ED Gut Function Technical Subcommittee. Stools that were collected on a day that falls within a diarrheal episode or where the last diarrheal episode ended less than or equal to 7 days ago met this definition. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age.
codebookDescription: 1 if considered a diarrhea stool (dprev3=1 or 1<= lastdiar <=7) ; 0 otherwise . Source=calculated.

label: Diarrheal stool collection #
definition: The Nth stool collected in a specific diarrheal episode, regardless of protocol Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Diarrheal stool samples were collected until 36 months of age.

label: Moderate-to-severe diarrhea by GEMS criteria within 2 days of stool collection
definition: Whether the participant met the GEMS definition of moderate-to-severe diarrhea within -/+ 2 days of stool collection. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age were included in analyses of gut function.
codebookDescription: GEMS definition of moderate/severe diarrhea for diarrhea days within +/2 days of stool collection. Source=illnessfull.

label: Per protocol diarrheal stool collection
definition: Whether this diarrheal stool sample was collected per the MAL-ED study protocol. Per protocol diarrheal stools included samples collected before the end of each diarrheal episode (whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day) as well as additional stool samples collected for a specific diarrhea episode after 14 study-defined diarrhea days in the same episode. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Diarrheal stool samples were collected until 36 months of age.

label: 1st monthly stool
definition: Whether this was the first monthly asymptomatic stool sample collected for this particular month of study, including archive-only stools. Note: most analyses used only the first asymptomatic monthly stool sample collected for each month and not additional per-protocol monthly sample collections. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age). First monthly asymptomatic samples collected at 13-14, 16-17, 19-20, 22-23 and 25-36 months of age were for archive.

label: Analysis stool, monthly
definition: Whether this was the first asymptomatic stool sample collected for a specific month and microbiology testing was completed according to the MAL-ED protocol. Use this variable to select appropriate diarrhea stools for microbiology analyses. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Cumulative 1st monthly stool count
definition: Cumulative count of the number of first monthly asymptomatic stool sample collected for this particular month of study to date, including archive-only stools. Note: most analyses used only the first asymptomatic monthly stool sample collected for each month and not additional per-protocol monthly sample collections. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age). First monthly asymptomatic samples collected at 13-14, 16-17, 19-20, 22-23 and 25-36 months of age were for archive.

label: Monthly archive only stool
definition: Whether this stool sample was a monthly asymptomatic collection for archive only. First monthly asymptomatic samples collected at 13-14, 16-17, 19-20, 22-23 and 25-36 months of age were for archive.

label: Monthly stool collection #
definition: The Nth stool collected in the sequence of asymptomatic monthly stool samples collected for a specific month, regardless of protocol. Occasionally, more than one non-diarrheal stool sample is collected in a specific month. Monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age.

label: Stool used for environmental enteropathy analysis
definition: Indicator to select the gut function analysis set of stool samples used in PMID: 28396264. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age were included in analyses of gut function.
codebookDescription: indicator variable 1 if the first stool for a given child/month; NA otherwise; used to select analysis set. Source=calculated.

Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Giardia ELISA performed
definition: Results of Giardia ELISA for this stool sample. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Protozoa ELISA testing completed
definition: Whether protozoal ELISA testing was completed (defined as having ELISA tests for Cryptosporidium, Entamoeba histolytica, and Giardia completed) for this stool sample. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Aeromonas Ct value, by TAC result
variable: tac::aeromonas | tac_60m_updated::aeromonas | ext_lab_bv_tacd::aero | ext_lab_bv_tac::aero | tac_aeromonas | aeromonas
definition: Cycle threshold for this stool sample to become positive for Aeromonas by TaqMan Array Card (TAC). Ct values of 35 were negative. Quantitative PCR for detection of enteric pathogens via TAC was performed on all available diarrheal and monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected from 0-24 months and at 60 months of age. For the histogram displayed on the ClinEpiDB website, the y-axis has been truncated to the second most abundant value if the most abundant value has over twice as many occurences. label: Aeromonas, by bacteriology result
definition: Results of Aeromonas identification by bacteriology culture for this stool sample. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebookDescription: Was Aeromonas detected?. From BDF form. Information comes from first collected sample, if there was a recollection sample. ''Aeromonas'' is the variable name for bdfaerotype collapsed into a yes/no variable. Source=BDF. yes, aeromonas spp =01; yes, aeromonas hydrophila =2; no =00

label: Atypical EPEC Ct value, by TAC result

Quantitative PCR for detection of enteric pathogens via TAC was performed on all available diarrheal and monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected from 0-24 months and at 60 months of age. label: Adenovirus, by ELISA result
definition: Results of Adenovirus ELISA for this stool sample. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebookDescription: Adenovirus result. Raw variable from FVF form. Use collapsed variable of ''adeno'' for results. Source=FVF. positive =01; negative =02; indeterminate =03

label: Target month for blood collection
definition: Blood samples were collected at 7, 15, 24, and 36 months of age. Hemoglobin and micronutrient status were assessed at 7, 15, 24, and 36 months of age. label: Target month for stool collection
definition: First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Diarrheal stool samples underwent microbiological testing and gut function testing. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age underwent microbiological testing and gut function testing. First monthly asymptomatic samples collected at 13-14, 16-17, 19-20, 22-23 and 25-36 months of age were archived.
codebookDescription: Target/scheduled month. Source=FRQ/FSQ/BRF/UCF/SRF/FSE/MOA. ..

Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Bacteriology testing completed
definition: Whether this stool sample underwent all bacteriology tests. Stool samples must have a completed Campylobacter ELISA test in addition to culture for Salmonella, Shigella, Vibrio, Yersinia, Aeromonas, and Plesiomonas for bacteriology testing to be considered complete. After culture, suspicious colonies were screened by biochemical tests to identify bacterial species. All presumptive Salmonella, Shigella, and Vibrio were confirmed by serotyping. Yersinia, Aeromonas, and Plesiomonas were confirmed by supplemental biochemical tests. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Stool type, gut function
definition: Stool type definition from the MAL-ED Gut Function Technical Subcommittee. 'Other stools' were samples where diarrhea was reported within the preceding 7 days and/or the lactulose:mannitol test was performed on the day of or day before stool collection. 'Asymptomatic stools' were stool samples that did not meet this definition of 'Other stools.' Only 'Asymptomatic stools' were included in the gut function analysis set used in PMID: 28396264. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age were included in analyses of gut function.
codebookDescription: gut function committee stool type definition 0 = asymptomatic; 1 if diarrhea within the preceding 7 days and/or LM test on the day of or day before stool collection. Source=calculated.
